parameters: The main character of our story is currently an old man
who had been through World War II and has been
diagnosed with PTSD. The game explores this man’s
dreams, and tries to get to the core of his PTSD, the
single event or many events that had caused this
trauma.
The dream will appear to take place in his childhood,
but certain events that can happen will flash the
scene to remind him of the war he was a part of, such
as the sound of rapid knocking will remind him of
gunshots, or a certain thing someone says will remind
him of a comrade in war who may or may not be alive.
In these flash-forwards to the war, the player will be
offered a choice, often a moral choice or a small
verbal choice. What the player chooses to do or say
will affect the dream, as all of it occurs in the main
character’s mind.
For example, denying some of the flash-forwards within
the dream as an event that couldn’t be happening will
cause less to appear, but the ones that do appear will
be much more traumatic and harder to ignore.
On the other hand, if you choose to live within the
flash-forward, it lasts longer with more dialogue, and
contains less terrifying events. Therefore, the events
that occur around the past of the protagonist is
really the main focus of the story.
Every jump from his childhood to the war will be
sudden, and sometimes unexpected. The entire game is
supposed to feel surreal, a dreamlike experience
conveying the best and worst of dreams. Events from
both his childhood and the war will occur.
